If we do this on top of social distancing maybe nurses and doctors would survive this pandemic without devastating morbidity.
Because we can’t stop it. We have to figure out every measure to slow it. You seem to be a politician that any argument that was backed up by facts you would consider. Open any procedure manual on infectious diseases, one of the PPE arsenal is shoe covers. It is simply another layer in this puzzle. And I am not addressing death, but hospitalization that might be effected. That’s what we need. Social distancing is key and and shouldn’t be eased. But if adding in the disinfectant of shoes and taking the temperature at stores stops only 10% of infections, I would take that 10% right now

snippet.textDisplay:
I am a medical doctor. When the individuals you love need emergency medical service, he/she will need to wait an hour because our medical system is full. If you are 40+ with hypertension, diabetes, heart disease or lung disease, you may experience your lungs being full of fluid. It could be your mom, dad, cousin, aunt, grandpa or grandma. You love that person to death. That person. That person. You will feel like you are drowning. Drowning for days. Gasping for air. Tossing and turning. You will cough up pink fluid. You are gasping for air. You are just trying to survive by just getting enough oxygen. The ventilator is barely keeping you alive. The brain will suffer long time casualties because your brain has been starved of oxygen for days. Your lung tissue is fully scared even after recovery. It will never be like your old self. There will be many folks like you, beside you. You are under quarantine. Your phone won't be there. Your family member won't be there. Your friends won't be there. You'll be alone. Die alone. If you die, you'll be mourned. Except your family will have to wait for their turn to mourn because there is a backlog of hundreds of other dead today. Time is ticking for our country.

And who will you turn to? I will be the one saving you. Do you hear that? It's the sirens bringing patient after patient after patient after patient at this very moment.
